{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585460"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:12:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:12:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14978"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14978"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.43,0.07,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66481"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51934"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8113"},{"type":"tags","id":"9951"},{"type":"tags","id":"9976"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18745"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66481"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EImmunoglobulins play essential roles in the immune response, including activation of the complement cascade. Different classes of immunoglobulins have distinct structural features that influence their biological functions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following immunoglobulins has the strongest complement-fixing ability?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IgM","IgG","IgA","IgD","IgE"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgM\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective complement-fixing immunoglobulin due to its pentameric structure. Each IgM molecule contains multiple binding sites for C1q, the first component of the classical complement pathway. A single IgM molecule can activate complement approximately 1000 times more effectively than a single \u003Cstrong\u003EIgG\u003C/strong\u003E molecule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA\u003C/strong\u003E does not activate the classical complement pathway but can activate the alternative pathway. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgD\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EIgE\u003C/strong\u003E do not activate complement at all. IgE primarily functions in allergic responses and defence against parasitic infections, while IgD appears to play a role in B-cell development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pentameric structure of IgM allows for enhanced avidity through multiple antigen binding sites and more efficient complement activation, making it particularly important in the early immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["IgM is the most potent complement-fixing immunoglobulin due to its pentameric structure with multiple C1q binding sites.","A single IgM molecule can activate complement approximately 1000 times more effectively than an IgG molecule.","IgA, IgD, and IgE do not activate the classical complement pathway."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Justiz Vaillant AA, Jamal Z, Patel P, et al. Immunoglobulin. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513460/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51934"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14978"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51934"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T16:05:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T16:33:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7666"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66481"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4908"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-14T17:03:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T17:03:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo